{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"781fd298-fee3-47f9-83e6-1ec47c9e3e8e","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the summary:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default fully-qualified test ID format**. Azure DevOps tracks history by test ID, so every test looks \"new.\" You can restore the v3 ID scheme by adding this to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr set it in your csproj if you prefer.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v3 the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` leaked the name of the first test — that was a **bug**, not a feature. In v4 the context at class-init time has **no associated test**, so accessing `TestName` throws.\n\nFix your code by removing that access:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context for logging via context.WriteLine() instead\n}\n```\n\nIf you truly need per-test names during setup, move the logic into `[TestInitialize]` where `TestContext` is bound to a specific test.\n\n## 3. Other v4 gotchas to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **Parallelism** | Class-level parallelism is now the **default**. Tests that assumed serial execution may break with race conditions. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or `DoNotParallelize` as needed. |\n| **Timeout** | `[Timeout]` now applies to the **test method only**, no longer includes `[TestInitialize]`/`[TestCleanup]`. Tight timeouts may need adjusting. |\n| **Assert.AreEqual on collections** | Some overloads now do **structural comparison** — tests that relied on reference equality may flip results. |\n| **`[DataRow]` display names** | Parameterized test display names changed, which also contributes to the \"new test\" problem in CI. |\n\nThe most impactful one for most teams is the **parallelism default**. If your test suite has shared state (static fields, databases, files), audit that first.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fcd3ef30-615b-4d7f-a999-a1ba27532717","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test Names (FQN) change** — MSTest v4 changed the default test ID format. The fully qualified name now includes parameter info differently, which causes Azure DevOps (and other CI systems) to see them as \"new\" tests with no history. This is the reason for lost test history.\n\n2. **`TestContext` in `[ClassInitialize]`** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` in a `[ClassInitialize]` method throws because at class-init time there's no individual test running yet. \n\nIn v3 this would return the first test's name, but v4 explicitly doesn't support that behavior anymore. Beyond these main issues, there are also changes to assembly-level parallelism now being enabled by default, shifts in how `DeploymentItem` and `DataRow` attributes work, and some APIs have been removed entirely.","outputTokens":894},"id":"fcdbb76f-4b77-4656-bc73-e1b7d98cf726","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:03:24.064Z","parentId":"6358d6ea-ca21-4d6f-afae-531f9712a440"}
